Aug 4 2007 	Little Shop of Antique Horrors	If you have a lot of money to spend and just love clutter and a good deal of stairs - this is your place! I work out 4 days a week but I must say that with luggage, or after a long day, those stairs were a challenge. This hotel is a red door on a side street, no name, and hard to find for your cabbie. There was a very nice man to meet us and help with my luggage on day one. The first thing to hit me was how dark, small and besieged with THINGS everywhere, on every surface. Some were quite humorous, some were plain creepy. The room itself was comfortable, yet old. Taking a bath was much easier than spraying the entire room with the shower arrangement. At this pricepoint I should have thought there would be a cooked breakfast, or at least something creative, but cereal was the best bet - cheese was going bad. Not a good taste first thing in the AM. The staff was friendly - if you got the two that were. Two others did not even speak to us; in fact, one made out with her boyfriend on the sofa in the sitting room and ignored the guests. She had better things to do, obviously. We stayed for 4 days, long enough to give you an adequate review. Had we payed 50 pound a night, I might have been more generous with an opinion - as that is what I felt it was worth.	
Jul 4 2007 	Ecclectic Ecstacy	Dear Traveler'sMiller's is a delightful, artistic/poetic of course and very eccentric hotel. There are a small number of rooms, our room and particularly our bed was sooooo comfortable (especially after lugging our suitcases all over Europe using public transportation). There is an open bar- (had a grand Pimm's Lemonade) the host has his own label of (was it Gin or Vodka?, antique books and books on key UK women and men (he must publish as well). The living room (as is the rest of the place) is jam packed with magazines, books, antiques and etc- all regularly dusted, and you can cozy up to the corner window and watch life go by one floor down. You feel like you are staying in your own flat in a grand neighborhood of boutiques and fun eateries. Very pleasant choices for a European style breakfast (e.g. meats cheeses breads fruit etc) come with the stay. It was quiet when we were there although we were able to visit with some of the guests. The staff were polite and helpful and probably have a lot of interesting stories to tell about us travelers. I think it is well worth the splurge, certainly is a special and unique lodging experience with all the amenities and all the character that the run of the mill hotels don't have. Enjoy!	
Jun 25 2007 	Very special.	Miller's is fantastic. It is absolutely rich in character and personality. There are only 7 rooms, you get a key to the entrance and to your room, so you feel like you're staying in your own place.There is art everywhere, and I mean every inch. The staff is friendlyand personal. Breakfast is good, and the breakfast room/ living room is also loaded with character. The place is old so don't expect an elevator, double glazed windows, air conditioning or perfect plumbing. I had no problem with any of that. We had plenty of hot water and a nice big double hung window. The location is superb. There are lots of places to eat around the corner and even downstairs! It's a nice residential area with boutiques on Westbourne Grove and the Portobello market is ten minutes away on foot. Hyde Park is also ten minutes away. From Westbourne Grove it's easy to take the bus directly to Oxford Street and the West End or to South Kensington and Knightsbridge or over thethames. I look forward to staying here again.	
May 21 2007 	Don't count on your reservation here!	This is a warning to anyone booking at Millers - have a back-up plan! Even if you receive a confirmation you may not actually have a room.Here's what happened to me:After much research, including reading all the reviews here on TripAdvisor, I called Millers and made a booking to spend 3 nights over the Memorial Day weekend 2007. I made the booking back in February 2007 via telephone and received a confirmation via email on Feburary 28.On May 16, just 1 week before we were supposed to arrive, I received an email from Millers saying they had a mix-up in their reservations and they did not have any room for me. They suggested another hotel, which was slightly more expensive (and in which I had no interest) and a 15% discount should I stay at Millers in the future.The reservationist - Matthew - called a few days later and cheerily asked if I got his email. I told him how appalled I was by the situation, and he told me that they had a temporary reservationist back in November who took a booking for 2 rooms but only reserved one, so they were giving my room to that person since they booked before I did. This was NOT a satisfactory explanation to me, particularly since when I called in February they still had other rooms available so clearly they were booting me out even though others had booked after me. I explained this but to no avail (which makes me wonder what the real story was for withdrawing my room, but I guess I will never know).Fortunately, with some scrambling around, I managed to get another reservation somewhere else at short notice. However, I am shocked and disappointed at Miller's appalling lack of regard for their customers. I can't imagine ever planning to go back there 15% discount or not, as I can't be sure whether they will actually have a reservation for me or not.Be warned if you book there!	
