May 2 2006	Den of iniquity? Nay Sir…if I may be so bold Den of Antiquity…	I am still reeling from a veritable tumble down the rabbit hole, into Wonderland. Not Alice’s Wonderland however, but the sumptuous, covert box of delights that is Miller’s Residence. Nestling in London’s Notting Hill, I found myself warmly installed amongst the flotsam and jetsam of a lifetime’s treasure hunting, stunning baroque interiors matched with evocative trinkets of a time long since gone. Picture the bizarre, the sinister, the curious, infused with a joviality and gin-spirited ambience to bring a flush of colour to the cheeks of the most pallid of maidens. And there I was, such a maiden, bedecked with all manner of delight, from the morning’s banquet through to the hazy rememberings of an evening supping mother’s ruin and singing hearty songs by the fire. As for the night time, oh Jupiter! How I wept with pleasure as I spied the decadent and delightful surroundings that were to house my sleeping self that night. There is not a person on this earth who would not benefit from time spent at this delicious little enclave of respite from the miasma of broken dreams that floats above the putrid city that is London town. A must.	
